<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-08-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-08-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="115" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 825.00/77.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Chilean
                                Chargé</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-08-25"><hi rend="italic">August 25,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 40.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your-note of the 17th instant, conveying the sad
                            intelligence, which has been received with sorrow, that the President of
                            Chile, Señor Don Pedro Montt, died at Bremen, Germany, on the preceding
                            day.</p>
                        <p>The grief of the Government and people of the United States, which would
                            have been profound in any event, is intensified by the personal
                            knowledge of President Montt’s high abilities and amiable qualities,
                            which they obtained during his recent visit to this country.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington
                            Wilson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>